TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing and class-based object-oriented features. It was created by Microsoft in 2012 and is now an open source project managed by the TypeScript team.

Duck typing is a concept in object-oriented programming where an object can be used if it implements or has the required methods or properties, regardless of its type. This means that if an object behaves like a duck, it can be treated as a duck even though it may not actually be a duck.

In TypeScript, duck typing is supported through interfaces. An interface defines a set of required methods or properties that a class must implement in order to conform to that interface. A class that implements all of the methods or properties defined in an interface can then be treated as if it were that interface type.

For example:

