The longest valid parentheses substring can be found using dynamic programming. We maintain two arrays left and right of equal lengths representing the number of left and right parentheses respectively encountered so far. Then, we iterate through the string and update the arrays accordingly. The maximum value in the left array at any point gives us the length of the longest valid parentheses substring ending at that point and the maximum value in the right array at any point gives us the length of the longest valid parentheses substring starting at that point. We compare these two values to get the length of the overall longest substring. 
```python
def longestValidParentheses(s):
    n = len(s)
    left = [0]*n
    right = [0]*n

    # Traverse through the string
    for i in range(n):
        if s[i] == '(':
            left[i] = left[i-1] + 1
        else:
            right[i] = right[i-1] + 1

    # Traverse again in reverse to fill left and right arrays
    for i in range(n-1,-1,-1):
        if s[i] == ')':
            left[i] = left[i+1] + 1
        else:
            right[i] = right[i+1] + 1

    # Get the length of the longest valid parentheses substring starting at each position
    max_length_start = [0]*n
    for i in range(1,n):
        max_length_start[i] = max(max_length_start[i-1],right[i-1])

    # Get the length of the longest valid parentheses substring ending at each position
    max_length_end = [0]*n
    for i in range(n-1,-1,-1):
        max_length_end[i] = max(max_length_end[i+1],left[i+1])    

    # Compare the lengths to find the longest valid parentheses substring
    max_length = 0
    for i in range(n):
        max_length = max(max_length,max_length_start[i]+max_length_end[i]-1)

    return max_length
```

This algorithm has time complexity O(n) where n is the length of the input string.

